article.headline: Kansas State 68, New Mexico 56
article.story: MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- After sitting out one year at a junior college in Michigan and then sustaining an injury in practice that he feared would sideline him for another season, David Hoskins is making the most of his time on the court. Hoskins scored 17 points, including 10 straight in the second half, and Kansas State closed with a 22-7 run to down New Mexico 68-56 on Wednesday night. "I thought I had done something bad," Hoskins said of the injury, which turned out to be a deep bruise. "Everything went through my head. My career flashed, everything flashed, and I just said there's no wasting time anymore." Kansas State (2-0) trailed by as many as 16 in the first half, but got within 35-26 by halftime. After closing to within three with 10:47 to go, Dramane Diarra scored inside and Cartier Martin added a basket a few minutes later to give Kansas State a 50-49 lead, its first since the game's opening minute. "They came out with a sense of urgency," New Mexico coach Ritchie McKay said. "K-State did a great job in the second half." New Mexico's David Chiotti scored to briefly put the Lobos back on top, but Hoskins scored on four of the Wildcats' next five possessions to take the lead for good. Kansas State outscored New Mexico 42-21 over the final 20 minutes. "I feel confident," said Hoskins, who redshirted last year at Schoolcraft College after playing his freshman year at Central Michigan. "I didn't necessarily put the game on my shoulders," he said. "Cartier Martin is the guy we depend on every night. Everybody else just has to fill in the blanks." Kansas State wouldn't have been within striking distance if not for Martin, who led the Wildcats with 22 points and 11 rebounds -- his second double-double in as many games. The junior guard was 9-of-13 from the field and scored 11 points in the first half to keep the Wildcats close. "Cartier kept us at least with a breath of air by halftime," coach Jim Wooldridge said. "We weren't dead." New Mexico (3-1), which hit 56 percent of its shots in the first half and was 6-of-10 from beyond the 3-point arc, struggled from the field down the stretch. The Lobos missed all 11 of their second-half 3-point attempts as Kansas State turned up the defensive pressure. "It started at the defensive end," Hoskins said. "We locked down and were running." Mark Walters hit four 3-pointers and scored 12 of his 16 points in the first half for the Lobos. Chiotti also finished with 16. Kansas State got off only three shots in its first nine possessions as New Mexico opened the game on a 13-1 run. Fueled by three consecutive 3-pointers from Walters, the lead ballooned to 30-14 with 4:30 to go in first half. But Tyler Hughes scored a couple of baskets inside and Martin rattled off six points to close the gap by halftime. "We had them down 16 in the first half and we let them go on that run," Chiotti said. "They just came out in the second half and beat us."
